The signs and symptoms linked with CMPA, ranges from colic and reflux to constipation and diarrhea, and makes diagnosis a real challenge. Every case of CMPA is also unique, so it helps to be aware of all the possible symptoms to look out for. There are three main categories of symptoms that include skin, digestive, respiratory, and more general symptoms as listed in the chart below*. These symptoms can appear immediately, within minutes or up to two hours of ingesting cow’s milk, or sometimes even after several hours or days, depending on the nature and sensitivity of the reaction.



If you think your baby is suffering from the signs and symptoms of CMPA or other food allergies, it is important to set up an appointment with your healthcare professional and prepare for your visit. Diagnosis of CMPA should always be made by a healthcare professional.


Breastfeed to StartFor approximately the first six months of your baby’s life, exclusive breastfeeding is recommended. If for any reason you are unable to breastfeed or when formula feeding is recommended, such as when your baby has been diagnosed with cow’s milk protein allergy, you will be directed by your child’s healthcare provider for recommendations on managing the allergy. This may include the use of a specialized formula.Introducing Solid FoodThe key to starting your baby on solid food, at 4- 6 months of age, is to introduce one food at a time. This way, if there is an allergic reaction, it’s easier to figure out which food is responsible. It is also important to avoid allergy-triggering foods such as eggs or fish as first foods.Introduce New Meals CarefullyAs you start introducing solid food, the midday meal should be introduced first, followed by the evening meal and finally the afternoon meal. On the first day, give your baby one to three spoonfuls of puréed foods, increasing the amount every day, until at the end of the week you are giving your child a whole portion.Cooked Foods are Easiest to DigestAlthough raw food is healthy, it is better to feed your infant cooked or steamed fruit and vegetables at first. Heated food is usually easier to digest, but you need to make sure the food is warm, not hot. As a rule of thumb, fruit and vegetables that your child tolerates well when cooked can eventually be introduced in their raw state.
Related ProductsALFAMINOTM INFANTView productBuy NowALFAMINOTM JUNIORView productBuy Now




